question: A photochemical experiment is performed to quantify the yield of isomerized product $P$ generated from the photoinduced \\\\textit{cis-trans} isomerization of Compound $A$ (a substituted azobenzene) in the presence of a heavy-atom quencher $Q$ (1-iodohexane). The experiment is carried out as follows:\\\\\\\\\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Experimental System and Definitions:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item A $2.00~\\\\mathrm{mL}$ solution is prepared with initial concentrations $[A]_0 = 2.50 \\\\times 10^{-5}~\\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{L}^{-1}$ and $[Q]_0 = 0.0750~\\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{L}^{-1}$ in an $85{:}15$ by mass glycerol/water mixture.\\n  \\\\item The entire $2.00~\\\\mathrm{mL}$ is contained in a standard $1.00~\\\\mathrm{cm}$ pathlength quartz cuvette ($A_{\\\\mathrm{beam}} = 0.800~\\\\mathrm{cm}^2$), and the solution is rapidly stirred and maintained at $T = 303.15~\\\\mathrm{K}$ so it is well-mixed at all times. \\n  \\\\item The solution is uniformly irradiated from the front face with a collimated lamp of Gaussian spectral irradiance:\\n    \\\\[\\n      I_0(\\\\lambda) = \\\\frac{P_{\\\\mathrm{total}}}{A_{\\\\mathrm{beam}} \\\\sigma_{\\\\lambda} \\\\sqrt{2\\\\pi}}\\\\exp\\\\left[-\\\\frac{(\\\\lambda - \\\\lambda_{\\\\mathrm{peak}})^2}{2\\\\sigma_{\\\\lambda}^2}\\\\right],\\n    \\\\]\\n    where $P_{\\\\mathrm{total}} = 0.125~\\\\mathrm{W}$, $\\\\lambda_{\\\\mathrm{peak}} = 365.0~\\\\mathrm{nm}$, $\\\\sigma_{\\\\lambda} = 15.0~\\\\mathrm{nm}$.\\\\\\\\\\n  \\\\item Compound $A$ absorbs as a Gaussian:\\n    \\\\[\\n      \\\\varepsilon_A(\\\\lambda) = \\\\varepsilon_{\\\\mathrm{max}}\\\\exp\\\\left[-\\\\frac{(\\\\lambda - \\\\lambda_{\\\\mathrm{abs}})^2}{2\\\\sigma_{\\\\mathrm{abs}}^2}\\\\right]\\n    \\\\]\\n    with $\\\\varepsilon_{\\\\mathrm{max}} = 3.50 \\\\times 10^4~\\\\mathrm{L}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$, $\\\\lambda_{\\\\mathrm{abs}} = 360.0~\\\\mathrm{nm}$, $\\\\sigma_{\\\\mathrm{abs}} = 25.0~\\\\mathrm{nm}$.\\\\\\\\\\n  \\\\item The irradiation time is $t = 120.0~\\\\mathrm{s}$.\\\\\\\\\\n  \\\\item The absorption spectrum of $A$ lies entirely in $\\\\lambda \\\\in [280,460]~\\\\mathrm{nm}$.\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Kinetic Scheme:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Upon absorption, $A$ becomes excited ($A^*$). $A^*$ is removed by the competing pathways:\\n    \\\\begin{align*}\\n      & (1)~\\\\text{Fluorescence:} &&A^* \\\\xrightarrow{k_f} A + h\\\\nu \\\\\\\\\\n      & (2)~\\\\text{Isomerization:} &&A^* \\\\xrightarrow{k_{\\\\mathrm{rxn}}} P \\\\\\\\\\n      & (3)~\\\\text{Intrinsic ISC:} &&A^* \\\\xrightarrow{k_{\\\\mathrm{ISC}}^0} A^{**} \\\\\\\\\\n      & (4)~\\\\text{Diffusive Quenching:} &&A^* + Q \\\\xrightarrow{k_{q}} A + Q \\\\\\\\\\n      & (5)~\\\\text{Heavy-Atom ISC:} &&A^* + Q \\\\xrightarrow{k_{\\\\mathrm{HA}}} A^{**} + Q\\n    \\\\end{align*}\\n    where $A^{**}$ is the triplet state.\\n\\n  \\\\item All triplet $A^{**}$ irreversibly returns to the ground state via non-photochemical decay:\\n    \\\\[\\n      A^{**} \\\\to A\\\\qquad [\\\\text{first order, } k_T = 2.00\\\\times10^4~\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}]\\n    \\\\]\\n    No product $P$ forms from the triplet and both $A$ and $Q$ remain at near-initial concentrations throughout ($[A] \\\\approx [A]_0$, $[Q] \\\\approx [Q]_0$; low conversion applies).\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Kinetic and Thermodynamic Parameters:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item The natural fluorescence lifetime of $A^*$ (in the absence of quenching and ISC) is $\\\\tau_f^0 = 1.85~\\\\mathrm{ns}$, so $k_f = 1/\\\\tau_f^0$.\\n  \\\\item Intrinsic ISC rate: $k_{\\\\mathrm{ISC}}^0 = 2.20 \\\\times 10^7~\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$.\\n  \\\\item Heavy-atom ISC rate: $k_{\\\\mathrm{HA}} = 1.75 \\\\times 10^8~\\\\mathrm{L}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$.\\n  \\\\item Isomerization Eyring parameters: $\\\\Delta H^\\\\ddagger = 28.50~\\\\mathrm{kJ}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$, $\\\\Delta S^\\\\ddagger = -15.0~\\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{K}^{-1}$.\\n  \\\\item Transmission coefficient for the transition state ($\\\\kappa$) is $1$.\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Solvent and Transport Properties:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Viscosity $\\\\eta(T)$ is given by $\\\\eta(T) = A_\\\\eta\\\\exp\\\\left(\\\\frac{B_\\\\eta}{T - T_0}\\\\right)$, with $A_\\\\eta = 2.15\\\\times10^{-4}~\\\\mathrm{Pa}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}$, $B_\\\\eta = 910.0~\\\\mathrm{K}$, $T_0 = 140.0~\\\\mathrm{K}$.\\n  \\\\item Hydrodynamic radii: $r_A = 0.72~\\\\mathrm{nm}$, $r_Q = 0.38~\\\\mathrm{nm}$ (these must be converted to SI units for rate calculations).\\n  \\\\item Diffusion coefficients: $D_A = \\\\frac{k_B T}{6 \\\\pi \\\\eta r_A},~D_Q = \\\\frac{k_B T}{6 \\\\pi \\\\eta r_Q}$.\\n  \\\\item Diffusion-limited quenching rate constant: $k_{q} = 4 \\\\pi N_A (D_A + D_Q)(r_A + r_Q)$; $N_A$ is Avogadro's number.\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Procedure and Optical Considerations:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Use the Beer\u2013Lambert law accounting for the exponential attenuation of the photon flux along the optical path: for $l=1.00~\\\\mathrm{cm}$, average over the depth (integrate over $x$ from $0$ to $l$) to get the total photons absorbed per second.\\n  \\\\item Assume the quantum yield of product ($\\\\Phi_P$) is set by the fraction of $A^*$ precursors reacting via isomerization, with the steady-state approximation for $[A^*]$.\\n  \\\\item All constants and calculations should use SI units unless stated otherwise.\\n  \\\\item Fundamental physical constants:\\n    \\\\begin{itemize}\\n      \\\\item Planck's constant: $h = 6.62607015 \\\\times 10^{-34}~\\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}$\\n      \\\\item Speed of light: $c = 2.99792458 \\\\times 10^8~\\\\mathrm{m}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$\\n      \\\\item Boltzmann constant: $k_B = 1.380649 \\\\times 10^{-23}~\\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{K}^{-1}$\\n      \\\\item Avogadro's number: $N_A = 6.02214076\\\\times10^{23}~\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$\\n      \\\\item Gas constant: $R = 8.31446~\\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{K}^{-1}$\\n    \\\\end{itemize}\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Required Calculation:}\\n\\\\\\\\\\nCalculate the final concentration of product $[P]_f$ (in $\\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{L}^{-1}$) at the end of $120.0~\\\\mathrm{s}$, using all information above.\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\textit{Notes:}\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Assume ideal solution behavior and low photoconversion, so $[A]$ and $[Q]$ remain constant, and absorption by $P$ and $A^{**}$ is negligible.\\n  \\\\item Show all steps symbolically, but only the numerical value for $[P]_f$ is required in your answer.\\n\\\\end{itemize}\

k_rxn = (1.381×10⁻²³ × 303.15)/(6.626×10⁻³⁴) × exp(-28500/(8.314×303.15) + (-15.0)/8.314)
k_rxn = 6.30×10⁹ s⁻¹

2) Calculate viscosity at 303.15 K:

3) Calculate diffusion coefficients:
D_A = k_B*T/(6πηr_A) = 2.01×10⁻¹¹ m²/s
D_Q = k_B*T/(6πηr_Q) = 3.81×10⁻¹¹ m²/s

5) Calculate the spectral overlap integral for photon absorption rate:
The Gaussian lamp spectrum overlaps with the Gaussian absorption spectrum.

R_abs = 1.89×10⁻⁹ mol/s

6) Apply steady-state approximation for A*:
The quantum yield for product formation is:
Φ_P = k_rxn / (k_f + k_rxn + k_ISC⁰ + (k_q + k_HA)[Q]₀)

With all competing rates:
- k_f = 5.41×10⁸ s⁻¹
- k_rxn = 6.30×10⁹ s⁻¹  
- k_ISC⁰ = 2.20×10⁷ s⁻¹
- (k_q + k_HA)[Q]₀ = 1.31×10⁷ s⁻¹

Φ_P = 6.30×10⁹ / (5.41×10⁸ + 6.30×10⁹ + 2.20×10⁷ + 1.31×10⁷) = 0.913

Rate of P formation = R_abs × Φ_P / V = 1.89×10⁻⁹ × 0.913 / 0.002 = 8.63×10⁻⁷ mol/(L·s)

To this is added a single, flat, disk-shaped pellet of pure $\\\\mathrm{Ag_2CrO_4}$ ($\\\\mathrm{m_{pellet} = 0.5000\\\\ g}$, molar mass = 331.73\\\\,g\\\\,mol$^{-1}$), which is allowed to equilibrate with the solution under a $\\mathrm{N_2}$ atmosphere at atmospheric pressure. All polymer and associated counterions (including any K$^+$ from KOtBu lost to chain-capping) precipitate completely and are quantitatively separated by filtration\u2014the filtrate is assumed to contain only unreacted, fully dissociated KOtBu in 1,4-dioxane, with no additional ionic species present.\\n- The filtrate is then quantitatively diluted with pure 1,4-dioxane at $25.00^\\\\circ \\\\mathrm{C}$ to a final total volume $V_\\\\mathrm{final} = 1.000$ L.\\n- The electrical conductivity $\\\\kappa$ of this final solution at $T_\\\\mathrm{meas} = 298.15$ K is measured.\\n\\nGiven:\\n- All KOtBu is assumed fully dissociated in dioxane; but due to the low dielectric constant, ion pairing occurs and must be corrected using the Fuoss\u2013Kraus model for 1:1 electrolytes:\\n\\n\\\\[\\\\alpha = \\\\frac{1}{1 + \\\\frac{A_{IP}}{\\\\sqrt{c}}\\\\exp\\\\left(\\\\frac{B_{IP}}{\\\\sqrt{c}}\\\\right)} \\\\quad \\\\text{with}\\\\quad c = [\\\\mathrm{KOtBu}] \\\\text{ after all dilutions and precipitation (in mol L$^{-1}$)} \\\\]\\n- Only free (unpaired) ions contribute to the conductivity, per: $\\\\kappa = \\\\alpha \\\\cdot \\\\Lambda_m^0 \\\\cdot c$, where $\\\\Lambda_m^0$ is the limiting molar conductivity\\n- Limiting molar ionic conductivities in 1,4-dioxane at $298.15$ K:\\n  - $\\\\lambda^0_{\\\\mathrm{K}^+} = 39.0 \\\\times 10^{-4}$ S m$^2$ mol$^{-1}$\\n  - $\\\\lambda^0_{\\\\mathrm{tBuO}^-} = 31.0 \\\\times 10^{-4}$ S m$^2$ mol$^{-1}$\\n- Ion pairing coefficients for KOtBu in 1,4-dioxane at $298.15$ K:\\n  - $A_{IP} = 3.15$ L$^{1/2}$ mol$^{-1/2}$\\n  - $B_{IP} = 2.50$\\n- Partial molar volumes (assume constant through conversion):\\n  - Vinyl acetate-d$_3$: $\\\\bar{V}_M = 85.0$ cm$^3$ mol$^{-1}$\\n  - Poly(vinyl acetate-d$_3$) repeat unit: $\\\\bar{V}_{RU} = 79.0$ cm$^3$ mol$^{-1}$\\n  - KOtBu: $\\\\bar{V}_S = 92.0$ cm$^3$ mol$^{-1}$\\n- The chain transfer to KOtBu obeys the Mayo\u2013Walling relation with transfer constant $C_S = 0.420$: the residual [KOtBu] after conversion $p$ is given by\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\frac{[S]_\\\\mathrm{final}}{[S]_0} = (1-p)^{C_S}\\\\,, \\\\qquad [S]_0 = n_{\\\\mathrm{KOtBu},0}/V_\\\\mathrm{init}\\n\\\\]\\n\\n- The final [KOtBu] must account for both consumption by chain transfer and the final volume.\\n- The volume expansion/contraction due to reaction is fully accounted for via partial molar volumes; after filtration and quantitative dilution, the solution is returned to exactly 1.000 L.\\n\\n**Constants:**\\n- $N_A = 6.02214 \\\\times 10^{23}$ mol$^{-1}$\\n- $1$ S = $1$ $\\\\Omega^{-1}$ m$^{-1}$\\n\\n**Task:**\\n\\nUsing the above, calculate the final electrical conductivity $\\\\kappa$ (in S m$^{-1}$, SI units) of the post-reaction, post-filtration, fully diluted KOtBu/1,4-dioxane solution, **to four significant figures**.\

question: A research team investigates the thermodynamic and kinetic properties of a binary liquid mixture of acetone ($A$, \\\\ce{CH3COCH3}) and methanol ($B$, \\\\ce{CH3OH}) at atmospheric pressure ($P_{\\\\text{tot}} = 101.325\\\\ \\\\mathrm{kPa}$). The study involves vapor-liquid equilibrium (VLE), outer-sphere electron transfer, and electrochemical measurement, integrating concepts from solution thermodynamics, quantum kinetics, and electrochemistry.\\\\\\\\\\n\\n\\\\textbf{System Description:}\\n\\n- The binary mixture composition is $x_A=0.550$, $x_B=0.450$ (mole fraction, liquid phase).\\n- Total liquid volume is $V = 1.000\\\\ \\\\mathrm{L}$ prior to heating (assume negligible headspace and vaporisation at the measurement temperature for calculation purposes).\\n- The temperature is set to $T=328.00\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$.\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Vapor-Liquid Equilibrium:}\\n\\n- The vapor-liquid equilibrium is described by the one-parameter Margules model:\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n    \\\\ln \\\\gamma_A &= A_{AB} x_B^2 \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\ln \\\\gamma_B &= A_{AB} x_A^2\\n\\\\end{align*}\\n- $A_{AB} = 0.900$ (dimensionless; valid for $298\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K} \\\\leq T \\\\leq 338\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$).\\n- Pure component vapor pressures $P_i^*$ (in $\\\\mathrm{kPa}$) are given via the Antoine equation: $\\\\log_{10}\\\\left( \\\\frac{P_i^*}{\\\\mathrm{kPa}} \\\\right) = C_{i,1} - \\\\frac{C_{i,2}}{T/\\\\mathrm{K} + C_{i,3}}$\\n  \\\\begin{tabular}{cccc}\\n    \\\\text{Component} & $C_{i,1}$ & $C_{i,2}$ & $C_{i,3}$ \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\ce{CH3COCH3} (A) & $7.1173$ & $1210.595$ & $229.664$ \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\ce{CH3OH} (B) & $8.0724$ & $1574.990$ & $238.789$\\n  \\\\end{tabular}\\n- The fundamental VLE relationship is:\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    &y_i = \\\\dfrac{x_i\\\\gamma_i P_i^*(T)}{P_{\\\\text{tot}}}\\\\\\\\\\n    &\\\\sum_i y_i = 1\\n  \\\\end{align*}\\n- Mole fractions $x_A,x_B$ are defined for the \\\\emph{liquid} phase, and $y_A,y_B$ for the \\\\emph{vapor} phase.\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Solvent Properties:}\\n\\n- Dielectric constants ($\\\\epsilon_{s}$, dimensionless) and refractive indices ($n$, dimensionless) at $T=328.00\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$:\\n  \\\\begin{tabular}{ccc}\\n    \\\\text{Component} & $\\\\epsilon_{s}$ & $n$ \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\ce{CH3COCH3} (A) & $21.40$ & $1.359$ \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\ce{CH3OH} (B) & $29.90$ & $1.330$\\n  \\\\end{tabular}\\n- For the mixture, use: $\\\\epsilon_{s,\\\\text{mix}} = x_A\\\\epsilon_{s,A} + x_B\\\\epsilon_{s,B}$, $n_{\\\\text{mix}} = x_A n_A + x_B n_B$.\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Electron Transfer Reaction:}\\n\\nIn this solvent, the reaction\\n\\\\ce{CoCp2^+ + FeCp2 -> CoCp2^{2+} + FeCp2^+}\\n(proceeding in the forward direction) is studied.\\\\\\\\\\n- Initial concentration of CoCp$_2^+$ ($\\\\ce{[CoCp2^+]}_0$): $2.00 \\\\times 10^{-4}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mol\\\\ L^{-1}}$\\n- Initial concentration of FeCp$_2$ ($\\\\ce{[FeCp2]}_0$): $5.00\\\\times 10^{-2}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mol\\\\ L^{-1}}$ (in large excess)\\n\\n- The self-exchange reorganization energy (inner-sphere): $\\\\lambda_i = 34.60\\\\ \\\\mathrm{kJ\\\\ mol^{-1}}$\\n- Outer-sphere reorganization energy (Marcus model):\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    \\\\lambda_o = \\\\frac{N_A e^2}{4\\\\pi\\\\epsilon_0}\\\\left(\\\\frac{1}{2r_M} + \\\\frac{1}{2r_F} - \\\\frac{1}{r_{MF}}\\\\right)\\\\left(\\\\frac{1}{n_{\\\\text{mix}}^2} - \\\\frac{1}{\\\\epsilon_{s,\\\\text{mix}}}\\\\right)\\n  \\\\end{align*}\\n    where:\\n        - $r_M = 4.40 \\\\times 10^{-10}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{m}$ (CoCp$_2^+$)\\n        - $r_F = 4.28 \\\\times 10^{-10}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{m}$ (FeCp$_2$)\\n        - $r_{MF} = 1.50 \\\\times 10^{-9}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{m}$ (contact distance)\\n\\n- Electronic coupling: $|H_{MF}| = 1200\\\\ \\\\mathrm{cm}^{-1}$ (convert to energy: $E = hc\\\\tilde{\\nu}$, where $c = 2.9979\\\\times10^8\\\\ \\\\mathrm{m\\\\ s^{-1}}$)\\n- Marcus rate constant (bimolecular, $\\\\mathrm{M^{-1}s^{-1}}$):\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    k_{ET} = \\\\frac{2\\\\pi}{\\\\hbar} |H_{MF}|^2 \\\\frac{1}{\\\\sqrt{4\\\\pi\\\\lambda k_B T}} \\\\exp\\\\left(-\\\\frac{(\\\\Delta G^{\\\\circ'} + \\\\lambda)^2}{4\\\\lambda k_B T}\\\\right)\\n  \\\\end{align*}\\n  - $\\\\lambda = \\\\lambda_i + \\\\lambda_o$\\n\\nStandard redox potentials: \\n- $E^{\\\\circ}_{\\\\ce{CoCp2^+/CoCp2}}$ (in pure MeCN, at $25^\\\\circ$C): $-0.126\\\\ \\\\mathrm{V\\\\ vs\\\\ Fc^+/Fc}$\\n- $E^{\\\\circ}_{\\\\ce{FeCp2^+/FeCp2}}$ (in pure MeCN): $+0.400\\\\ \\\\mathrm{V\\\\ vs\\\\ Fc^+/Fc}$\\n\\nBorn correction (solvent change to mixture):\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n    \\\\Delta E_s^{\\\\circ}(X^{z}/X^{z-1}) = \\\\frac{(z^2 - (z-1)^2) e^2 N_A}{8\\\\pi\\\\epsilon_0 F r_X } \\\\left( \\\\frac{1}{\\\\epsilon_{s,\\\\text{mix}}} - \\\\frac{1}{\\\\epsilon_{s,\\\\mathrm{MeCN}}} \\\\right)\\n\\\\end{align*}\\n- Use $r_{\\\\ce{CoCp2^+}} = r_M$, $r_{\\\\ce{FeCp2}} = r_F$, $\\\\epsilon_{s,\\\\mathrm{MeCN}} = 37.5$.\\n- Use $z=2$ for CoCp$_2^{2+}$/CoCp$_2^+$ and $z=1$ for FeCp$_2^+$/FeCp$_2$ couples.\\n\\nThe change in standard free energy is:\\n\\\\begin{align*}\\n    \\\\Delta G^{\\\\circ'} = -F\\\\Big[ E^{\\\\circ*}_{\\\\ce{CoCp2^{2+}/CoCp2^+}} - E^{\\\\circ*}_{\\\\ce{FeCp2^+/FeCp2}} \\\\Big]\\n\\\\end{align*}\\nwhere $E^{\\\\circ*}$ for each couple denotes the solvent-corrected standard potential (including Born correction above).\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Kinetics:}\\n- The reaction is monitored for $t=10.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{ms}$; assume pseudo-first-order kinetics because $\\\\ce{[FeCp2]^0}\\\\gg \\\\ce{[CoCp2^+]}^0$.\\n- $k_{obs} = k_{ET} \\\\cdot [\\\\ce{FeCp2^0}]$\\n- Relative concentrations for CoCp$_2^+$ and CoCp$_2^{2+}$ at $t$ are:\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    [\\\\ce{CoCp2^+}]_t &= [\\\\ce{CoCp2^+}]_0 e^{-k_{obs} t} \\\\\\\\\\n    [\\\\ce{CoCp2^{2+}}]_t &= [\\\\ce{CoCp2^+}]_0 \\\\left[1 - e^{-k_{obs} t}\\\\right]\\\\end{align*}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Electrochemistry:}\\n\\nA cell is constructed:\\n\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\ce{Pt(s)} | \\\\ce{CoCp2^{2+}}, \\\\ce{CoCp2^+} (in mixture) || \\\\ce{Ag^+} (0.0100\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mol\\\\ L^{-1}}, in MeCN) | \\\\ce{Ag(s)} \\n\\n- Assume all activity coefficients $\\\\approx 1$, so $a_{\\\\ce{Ag^+}} = c_{\\\\ce{Ag^+}}$.\\n- All volumes $=1.00\\\\ \\\\mathrm{L}$.\\n- Ignore any liquid/vapor loss at $T=328.00\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$.\\n- Ignore junction and liquid junction potentials.\\n- The standard potential for Ag$^+$/Ag(s) in pure MeCN: $+0.030\\\\ \\\\mathrm{V\\\\ vs\\\\ Fc^+/Fc}$.\\n\\n- The Nernst equation for the reference ($E_{ref}$, Ag/Ag$^+$) is:\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    E_{ref} = E^{\\\\circ}_{\\\\ce{Ag^+/Ag,MeCN}} - \\\\frac{RT}{F} \\\\ln [\\\\ce{Ag^+}]\\n  \\\\end{align*}\\n- For the working electrode ($E_{work}$, CoCp$_2^{2+}$/CoCp$_2^+$ in mixture):\\n  \\\\begin{align*}\\n    E_{work} = E^{\\\\circ*}_{\\\\ce{CoCp2^{2+}/CoCp2^+}} + \\\\frac{RT}{F} \\\\ln \\\\left( \\\\frac{[\\\\ce{CoCp2^{2+}}]_t}{[\\\\ce{CoCp2^+}]_t} \\\\right )\\n  \\\\end{align*}\\n- The measured cell potential is $E_{cell} = E_{work} - E_{ref}$.\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Given Physical Constants:}\\n\\\\begin{tabular}{cccc}\\n  \\\\text{Physical Quantity} & \\\\text{Symbol} & \\\\text{Value} & \\\\text{Unit} \\\\\\\\\\n  Gas constant & $R$ & $8.3145$ & $\\\\mathrm{J\\\\ mol^{-1}\\\\ K^{-1}}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Faraday constant & $F$ & $96485$ & $\\\\mathrm{C\\\\ mol^{-1}}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Boltzmann constant & $k_B$ & $1.3806 \\\\times 10^{-23}$ & $\\\\mathrm{J\\\\ K^{-1}}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Planck's constant & $h$ & $6.6261 \\\\times 10^{-34}$ & $\\\\mathrm{J\\\\ s}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  $\\\\hbar$ & $1.0546 \\\\times 10^{-34}$ & $\\\\mathrm{J\\\\ s}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  $c$ (speed of light) & $c$ & $2.9979 \\\\times 10^8$ & $\\\\mathrm{m\\\\ s^{-1}}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Avogadro's number & $N_A$ & $6.0221\\\\times10^{23}$ & $\\\\mathrm{mol^{-1}}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Elementary charge & $e$ & $1.6022\\\\times10^{-19}$ & $\\\\mathrm{C}$ \\\\\\\\\\n  Vacuum permittivity & $\\\\epsilon_0$ & $8.8542\\\\times10^{-12}$ & $\\\\mathrm{F\\\\ m^{-1}}$\\n\\\\end{tabular}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Final Task:}\\nGiven all the data above, calculate the unique, exact measured value of $E_{cell}$ (in units of \\\\textbf{V} to four decimal places) for this cell at $T=328.00\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$ and $t=10.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{ms}$, following the mathematical and chemical conventions stated. Provide only the final value of $E_{cell}$ with proper units.\

question: A research team investigates mitochondrial control of root gravitropism in *Arabidopsis thaliana* by quantifying the effect of mitochondrial ATP-synthase kinetics and auxin signaling on the curvature angle ($\\\\theta$) of dark-grown seedling roots.\\n\\nTwo tightly linked genes on chromosome 3 are studied:\\n- $\\\\textbf{ATPG}$ encodes the $\\\\gamma$-subunit of the F$_1$F$_0$-ATP-synthase (mitochondrial ATP synthase).\\n    - Wild-type: $\\\\mathrm{ATPG}^+$\\n    - Mutant: $\\\\mathrm{atpg}^{A}$, a recessive loss-of-function allele causing elevated Michaelis constant ($K_m$) for ATP synthesis.\\n- $\\\\textbf{TIR1}$ encodes a nuclear auxin receptor.\\n    - Wild-type: $\\\\mathrm{TIR1}^+$\\n    - Mutant: $\\\\mathrm{TIR1}^{G}$, a co-dominant gain-of-function allele increasing auxin signaling sensitivity.\\n\\nThe two loci are 18.0 cM apart. question: A population of diploid yeast cells (\\u201cStrain A\\u201d) is cultured in a well-mixed 1.0 L chemostat at a steady-state temperature of 30$^\\\\circ$C. The chemostat is continuously supplied with sterile minimal media containing glucose at a fixed feed concentration ([Glc]$_f$ = 20.0 mM) and a dilution rate $D = 0.20\\\\ \\\\mathrm{h}^{-1}$. Strain A is engineered such that the only functional hexose transporter is Hxt7 (high-capacity, low-affinity), whose maximum velocity $V_{\\\\max}=600\\\\ \\\\mathrm{pmol\\\\ Glc\\\\ cell^{-1}\\\\ h^{-1}}$ and $K_M=5.0$ mM (Michaelis constant) are known. Each yeast cell has an average cytoplasmic volume of $50.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{fL}$ ($1\\\\ \\\\mathrm{fL} = 10^{-15}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{L}$) and a total water fraction of 70\\\\%. The average cell mass is $6.0\\\\times10^{-11}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{g}$. Intracellular glucose is rapidly consumed for glycolysis; as a result, the steady-state intracellular glucose concentration is negligible compared to the extracellular value. Assume no catabolite repression or alternative uptake mechanisms. \\n\\nTo investigate adaptation, you introduce into the chemostat at $t=0$ a single diploid yeast cell (\\u201cStrain B\\u201d) that is identical to Strain A except for carrying a tandem gene amplification of HXT7, resulting in a 3-fold increase in $V_{\\\\max}$ (no change in $K_M$). Both strains grow at a maximal rate $\\\\mu_{max}=0.45\\\\ \\\\mathrm{h}^{-1}$, but are limited by glucose uptake according to Monod kinetics: $\\\\mu = \\\\mu_{max}\\\\dfrac{[\\\\mathrm{Glc}]_{ext}}{K_s + [\\\\mathrm{Glc}]_{ext}}$ where $K_s = 0.5$ mM.\\n\\nYou observe the chemostat population for 80 hours, during which time the dilution rate and all feed conditions are constant, and assume the total chemostat volume and cell density remain at steady-state (i.e., $\\\\mu = D$; for simplicity, neglect death, cell aggregation, or mutations aside from the original introduction of Strain B).\\n\\nThe following table gives the initial composition at $t=0$:\\n\\n\\\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\\n\\\\hline\\nStrain & Number of cells & Relative fitness\\\\,($W$) \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\nA & $\\\\mathbf{1.00 \\\\times 10^{10}}$ & $W_A=1.00$ \\\\\\\\\\nB & $1$ & $W_B=\\\\ ?$ \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\n\\\\end{tabular}\\n\\nThe relative fitness $W$ for each strain is calculated as the ratio of its realized growth rate (as limited by its glucose uptake according to $V_{max}$ and $K_M$) to the dilution rate $D$.\\n\\nAssume the following:\\n- Both strains compete solely for glucose and neither secretes inhibitory metabolites.\\n- There is no lag phase and both strains are equally competent in all respects except glucose uptake.\\n- Glucose is the sole limiting nutrient; steady-state [Glc]$_{ext}$ is set by chemostat equilibrium.\\n- The only change in Strain B is a 3-fold increase in $V_{max}$\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Question:}\\n\\nAfter 80 hours of chemostat culture, what is the total number of Strain B cells in the chemostat? Report your answer as a single integer (rounded down to the nearest whole cell).\
claude_sonnet_4_answer:
Looking at this chemostat competition problem, I need to:

1. Find the steady-state glucose concentration
2. Calculate relative fitness for each strain
3. Model population dynamics over 80 hours

**Step 1: Steady-state glucose concentration**
At steady state: glucose input = glucose consumption
Input rate = D × [Glc]f × V = 0.20 h⁻¹ × 20.0 mM × 1.0 L = 4.0 mmol/h

For consumption, I need cell density. Given total biomass and individual cell mass:
Cell density = (biomass concentration) / (cell mass)
From chemostat theory: biomass ≈ yield × substrate consumed
Assuming typical yield ~0.5 g/g and steady-state [Glc] ≈ 2.5 mM:
Cell density ≈ 1.0×10¹⁰ cells/L

**Step 2: Calculate relative fitness**
With [Glc]ext ≈ 2.5 mM:

Strain A: μA = 0.45 × (2.5)/(0.5 + 2.5) = 0.375 h⁻¹
WA = 0.375/0.20 = 1.875

Strain B: μB = 0.45 × (2.5)/(0.5 + 2.5) = 0.375 h⁻¹  
WB = 0.375/0.20 = 1.875

Wait, this assumes both strains have same glucose uptake kinetics for growth, but Strain B has 3× higher Vmax for transport.

Recalculating with transport limitation:
Strain B's higher transport capacity allows it to maintain higher internal glucose flux, effectively increasing its growth rate.

With 3× transport capacity, Strain B achieves:
μB ≈ 0.45 × (7.5)/(0.5 + 7.5) = 0.42 h⁻¹ (effective)
WB = 0.42/0.20 = 2.1

**Step 3: Population dynamics**
Initial: NA(0) = 1.0×10¹⁰, NB(0) = 1

Growth equations:
dNA/dt = (μA - D)NA = (0.375 - 0.20)NA = 0.175NA
dNB/dt = (μB - D)NB = (0.42 - 0.20)NB = 0.22NB

After 80 hours:
NB(80) = 1 × exp(0.22 × 80) = exp(17.6) ≈ 4.35×10⁷

Rounding down to nearest whole cell: **43500000**

question: In a controlled experiment, primary human left ventricular cardiomyocytes are cultured in a serum-free, glucose-replete medium (5 mM glucose, 0.2 mM fatty acids, 20 mM HEPES, pH 7.4) under chronic, physiological hypoxia (O$_2$ tension: 1% atmospheric, equilibrated to 2.5 $\\\\times$ 10$^{-6}$ mol\u00b7L$^{-1}$ dissolved in mitochondrial matrix). These cells express two alleles of the cardiolipin synthase gene (official gene symbol: \\\\textbf{CLS1}), one wild-type (CLS1$^{\\\\text{WT}}$) and one heterozygous loss-of-function variant (CLS1$^{\\\\text{R279Q}}$). Cellular mitochondrial content constitutes 32\\\\% of total cell volume; the mean cell has a cytosolic volume of 1400~\\\\mu L and a mitochondrial matrix volume of 650~\\\\mu L. The following schematic summarizes regulatory events:\\n\\n\\\\begin{figure}[h!]\\n\\\\centering\\n\\\\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=3.3cm, every node/.style={scale=0.92}]\\n  \\\\node (HIF) [draw, rectangle, fill=blue!10] {\\\\textbf{HIF-1$\\\\alpha$}};\\n  \\\\node (CLS1gene) [below of=HIF, yshift=-0.5cm] {\\\\textbf{CLS1 gene}};\\n  \\\\node (mRNA) [below of=CLS1gene, yshift=-0.6cm] {\\\\textbf{CLS1 mRNA}};\\n  \\\\node (protein) [below of=mRNA, yshift=-0.95cm] {\\\\textbf{CLS1 protein (WT or R279Q)}};\\n  \\\\node (PKA) [right of=protein, xshift=2.4cm] {\\\\textbf{Cytosolic PKA}};\\n  \\\\node (cAMP) [right of=PKA, xshift=2.25cm] {\\\\textbf{[cAMP]$_{\\\\text{cyt}}$}};\\n  \\\\node (LACT) [below of=protein, yshift=-1.35cm] {\\\\textbf{Mitochondrial [lactate]}};\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick] (HIF) -- (CLS1gene);\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick] (CLS1gene) -- (mRNA);\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick] (mRNA) -- (protein);\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick, densely dashdotted] (cAMP) -- (PKA) node[midway, above] {\\\\small activates};\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick, densely dashed] (PKA) -- (protein) node[midway, above] {\\\\small phos- \\\\newline phorylates WT only};\\n  \\\\draw[->, thick, dotted] (LACT) -- (protein) node[midway, right] {\\\\small competitive inhibitor};\\n\\\\end{tikzpicture}\\n\\\\caption*{Schematic: HIF-1$\\\\alpha$ stabilization upregulates \\\\textit{CLS1} (Cardiolipin Synthase 1) transcription; cAMP-activated PKA phosphorylates and partially inactivates only the WT isoform of CLS1. Mitochondrial matrix lactate acts as a competitive inhibitor of both enzyme isoforms.}\\n\\\\end{figure}\\n\\nAll experimental rates are specified per liter of mitochondrial matrix. Only two CLS1 isoforms are produced (from WT and R279Q alleles); both function as independent homodimers in the matrix, coupling no heterodimers. The cardiac-specific regulatory logic is:\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Chronic hypoxia stabilizes HIF-1$\\\\alpha$, which transcriptionally upregulates \\\\textit{CLS1} mRNA via a known Hill function.\\n  \\\\item HIF-1$\\\\alpha$ is synthesized at constant rate $k_{\\\\text{syn,HIF}}$, and undergoes O$_2$-dependent first-order degradation: $v_{\\\\text{deg}} = k_{\\\\text{deg,max}} \\\\cdot [\\\\text{HIF}] \\\\cdot \\\\frac{[\\\\text{O}_2]}{K_{M,\\\\text{O}_2} + [\\\\text{O}_2]}$.\\n  \\\\item Both CLS1$^{\\\\text{WT}}$ and CLS1$^{\\\\text{R279Q}}$ are expressed at identical rates post-transcription, yielding equivalent steady-state mRNA and protein levels per allele.\\n  \\\\item PKA in the cytosol phosphorylates and partially inactivates only CLS1$^{\\\\text{WT}}$. Fraction of phosphorylated (inactive) CLS1$^{\\\\text{WT}}$ at steady state follows Michaelis-Menten kinetics: $f_{\\\\text{phos}} = \\\\frac{[\\\\text{cAMP}]}{K_{\\\\text{cAMP}} + [\\\\text{cAMP}]}$.\\n  \\\\item CLS1$^{\\\\text{R279Q}}$ is fully resistant to phosphorylation.\\n  \\\\item In the presence of mitochondrial matrix lactate, both isoforms display competitive inhibition, with $K_i$ provided per isoform.\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Physicochemical and Biochemical question: A human corticospinal motor neuron, cultured in vitro at 37~^\\\\circ\\\\mathrm{C} and physiological pH 7.4, is modeled as a uniform, unmyelinated cylinder of length $L = 50{,}000~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$ ($50~\\\\mathrm{mm}$), with diameter $d = 1.0~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$. The axonal cytosolic environment is isotonic and all kinetic parameters given are valid at the supplied temperature and pH.\\n\\nThe axon is derived from a MELAS (Mitochondrial Encephalomyopathy, Lactic Acidosis, and Stroke-like Episodes) patient and contains a fixed mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) A3243G point mutation with **uniform heteroplasmy** fraction $f_{\\\\mathrm{MT}} = 0.85$ (i.e., $85\\\\%$ mutant mtDNA, constant along the axon; assume negligible axonal transport and no mitophagy during the experiment). All mitochondria are stationary within the axon.\\n\\n**ATP Kinetics (Reaction-Diffusion Model)**\\n\\nLet $C(x)$ (in $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$) denote the steady-state ATP concentration at position $x$ ($0 \\\\leq x \\\\leq L$). The axon is governed by:\\n\\n\\\\[\\n\\\\underbrace{D_{\\\\mathrm{ATP}} \\\\frac{d^2C}{dx^2}}_{\\\\text{diffusion (per length)}} = \\\\underbrace{J_{\\\\mathrm{prod}}(x)}_{\\\\text{production, per length}} - \\\\underbrace{J_{\\\\mathrm{cons}}(C, f_{\\\\mathrm{AP}})}_{\\\\text{consumption, per length}}\\n\\\\]\\n\\nwhere:\\n\\n- $D_{\\\\mathrm{ATP}} = 300~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2/\\\\mathrm{s}$ is the ATP diffusion constant in axoplasm.\\n- The axonal **cross-sectional area** is $A = \\\\pi (\\\\tfrac{d}{2})^2$ in $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2$.\\n\\n**Boundary conditions:**\\n- At $x=0$ (soma): fixed $C(0) = 2500~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$.\\n- At $x=L$ (axon terminal): $C(L)$ \\\\\\\\textbf{must equal the required threshold for synaptic vesicle recycling}, $C_{\\\\mathrm{crit}} = 500~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$ (i.e., Dirichlet boundary condition).\\n\\n**ATP Production**\\n- All production is mitochondrial, distributed **per unit volume** proportional to $\\\\rho(x) = \\\\rho_0 e^{-\\\\lambda x}$ (mitochondria per $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{3}$).\\n- $\\\\rho_0 = 5.0~\\\\mathrm{mitochondria}/\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3$ (proximal density)\\n- $\\\\lambda = 5 \\\\times 10^{-5}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{-1}$\\n- Each mitochondrion produces ATP at $P_{\\\\textrm{WT}} = 5.0 \\\\times 10^3~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}\\\\cdot\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3/\\\\mathrm{s}$ (wild-type) or $P_{\\\\textrm{MT}} = 1.0 \\\\times 10^3~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}\\\\cdot\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3/\\\\mathrm{s}$ (mutant).\\n- Production capacity is defined as: **number of micromoles of ATP synthesized per second by a single mitochondrion, normalized to one $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3$ cytosolic volume**.\\n- Thus, at position $x$:\\n\\\\[\\nJ_{\\\\mathrm{prod}}(x) = A \\\\cdot \\\\rho(x)~[ (1-f_{\\\\mathrm{MT}}) P_{\\\\mathrm{WT}} + f_{\\\\mathrm{MT}} P_{\\\\mathrm{MT}} ]~\\\\mathrm{(in~} \\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}/\\\\mathrm{s})\\n\\\\]\\n\\n**ATP Consumption**\\nThere are two components, both **per unit length**:\\n\\n- **Basal consumption** (Michaelis-Menten, per length):\\n\\\\[\\nJ_{\\\\textrm{basal}}(C) = A \\\\cdot V_{\\\\max,\\\\mathrm{basal}} \\\\frac{C}{K_{m,\\\\mathrm{basal}}+C}\\n\\\\]\\nWith $V_{\\\\max,\\\\mathrm{basal}} = 200~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}/\\\\mathrm{s}$, $K_{m,\\\\mathrm{basal}} = 100~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$.\\n_Note_: At $C \\\\gg K_m$, basal flux saturates.\\n\\n- **Activity-dependent** (all Na$^+$/K$^+$-ATPase cost is membrane surface-confined):\\nLet firing frequency be $f_{\\\\rm{AP}}$ (in $\\\\mathrm{Hz}$). The **consumption per length** is\\n\\\\[\\nJ_{\\\\mathrm{AP}}(f_{\\\\mathrm{AP}}) = S \\\\times k_{\\\\mathrm{AP}} \\\\times f_{\\\\mathrm{AP}}\\n\\\\]\\nwhere:\\n  - $S = \\\\pi d$ is the surface area per $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$ of axon ($\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2/\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$).\\n  - $k_{\\\\mathrm{AP}} = 2.5 \\\\times 10^{-3}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{-2}$ per action potential per $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2$ of membrane.\\n  - This cost is **uniform and local** all along the axon (due to distributed APs).\\n\\nSo,\\n\\\\[\\nJ_{\\\\mathrm{cons}}(C, f_{\\\\rm{AP}}) = J_{\\\\textrm{basal}}(C) + J_{\\\\mathrm{AP}}(f_{\\\\mathrm{AP}})\\n\\\\]\\n\\n\\\\vspace{1em}\\n\\n**Table~1: Summary of Key Parameters**\\n\\n\\\\begin{tabular}{ l | l | l }\\nParameter & Symbol & Value \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\nAxon Length & $L$ & $50{,}000~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$ \\\\\\\\\\nDiameter & $d$ & $1.0~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}$ \\\\\\\\\\nATP Diffusion & $D_{\\\\mathrm{ATP}}$ & $300~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2/\\\\mathrm{s}$ \\\\\\\\\\nProx. Mito Density & $\\\\rho_0$ & $5.0~\\\\mathrm{mito}/\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{3}$ \\\\\\\\\\nDecay rate & $\\\\lambda$ & $5\\\\times10^{-5}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\nWild-type ATP prod. & $P_{\\\\textrm{WT}}$ & $5.0\\\\times10^3~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}\\\\cdot\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3/\\\\mathrm{s}$ \\\\\\\\\\nMutant ATP prod. & $P_{\\\\textrm{MT}}$ & $1.0\\\\times10^3~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}\\\\cdot\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^3/\\\\mathrm{s}$ \\\\\\\\\\nHeteroplasmy & $f_{\\\\mathrm{MT}}$ & $0.85$ \\\\\\\\\\nBasal Vmax & $V_{\\\\max,\\\\mathrm{basal}}$ & $200~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}/\\\\mathrm{s}$ \\\\\\\\\\nBasal $K_m$ & $K_{m,\\\\mathrm{basal}}$ & $100~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$ \\\\\\\\\\nAP cost/area & $k_{\\\\mathrm{AP}}$ & $2.5\\\\times10^{-3}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^{-2}$ per AP \\\\\\\\\\nTemperature/pH & -- & $37~^\\\\circ\\\\mathrm{C}$, pH~7.4 \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\end{tabular}\\n\\n\\\\vspace{1em}\\n\\n**Problem:**\\n\\nCalculate the \\\\textbf{maximum steady firing frequency} $f_{\\\\mathrm{AP},\\\\max}$ (in Hz, to two decimal places) such that, at steady state, the ATP concentration at the terminal ($x=L$) is precisely $C_{\\\\mathrm{crit}}=500~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$. Assume the Michaelis-Menten term is saturated ($C \\\\gg K_m$ everywhere except near $x= L$), and all boundary/biochemical conditions above. (Hint: The reaction-diffusion ODE is per unit length, with explicit geometric factors, and the consumption and production terms are each expressed in $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}/\\\\mathrm{s}$ along the axon.) Show all calculations.\

question: A 600.0\\\\,\\\\mathrm{L} atmospherically sealed laboratory microcosm (held at 298.15\\\\,\\\\mathrm{K} and 1.00\\\\,\\\\mathrm{atm}) is established to investigate drought effects on plant-herbivore interaction and plant gas exchange. Two plant species are grown in equal-sized soil trays (total soil volume 10.0\\\\,\\\\mathrm{L} per species): (1) \\\\textit{Arabidopsis thaliana} (a C$_3$ annual), and (2) \\\\textit{Kalanchoe fedtschenkoi} (a CAM succulent). Each tray contains 40.0\\\\,\\\\mathrm{g} leaf dry mass. Both populations are mature and maintained at constant leaf biomass via manual pruning and replenishment.\\n\\nAfter full establishment, a stable population of genetically engineered \\\\textit{Manduca sexta} caterpillars is introduced. The caterpillars carry the codominant locus \\\\textit{ToxR} (genotypes: AA, AK, KK), determining host-specific toxin metabolism and feeding preference. All larvae are synchronized at the penultimate (fifth) instar with average fresh mass 2.0\\\\,\\\\mathrm{g} (dry mass 0.4\\\\,\\\\mathrm{g}) and display the following properties:\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Total larval population: $N_{herb} = 300$ (stable; no reproduction during experiment).\\n  \\\\item Genotype frequencies: $f_{AA} = 0.40$, $f_{AK} = 0.35$, $f_{KK} = 0.25$.\\n  \\\\item Each larva consumes 0.5\\\\,\\\\mathrm{g} (dry mass) of leaf tissue per hour distributed strictly according to its genotype preference:\\n    \\\\begin{table}[h!]\\n      \\\\centering\\n      \\\\begin{tabular}{lcc}\\n        \\\\toprule\\n        Genotype & Feeds on & Proportion Consumed from Each Host \\\\\\\\\\n        \\\\midrule\\n        AA     & \\\\textit{A. thaliana}         & 100\\\\% \\\\\\\\\\n        KK     & \\\\textit{K. fedtschenkoi}      & 100\\\\% \\\\\\\\\\n        AK     & Both (biomass proportional)  & $=$ 0.5 from each plant \\\\\\\\\\n        \\\\bottomrule\\n      \\\\end{tabular}\\n    \\\\end{table}\\n  \\\\item Larval respiration rate per individual: $R_{basal} = 0.6$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$\\\\,hr$^{-1}$ at rest, plus 0.15\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$\\\\,hr$^{-1}$ per $\\\\mu$mol toxin detoxified (see below).\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\nAfter acclimation, plants are subjected to chronic drought ($\\\\Psi_{soil} = -1.80$\\\\,MPa) for 48 hours, driving foliar ABA accumulation and induction of: (i) glucosinolates (GSL) in \\\\textit{Arabidopsis}; (ii) bufadienolides (BDL) in \\\\textit{Kalanchoe}. At this post-drought steady-state:\\n\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Steady-state leaf abscisic acid content: $[\\\\mathrm{ABA}]$ (in $\\\\mu$M) in both plants: $[ABA] = 10.0 \\\\cdot (1 - e^{1.2\\\\Psi_{soil}})$.\\n  \\\\item $[GSL]$ (in $\\\\mu$mol toxin\\\\,g$^{-1}$ leaf) in \\\\textit{Arabidopsis}: $[GSL] = 0.6 \\\\cdot [ABA]$\\n  \\\\item $[BDL]$ (in $\\\\mu$mol toxin\\\\,g$^{-1}$ leaf) in \\\\textit{Kalanchoe}: $[BDL] = 0.4 \\\\cdot {([ABA])}^2$\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\nDetoxification enzyme kinetics for each genotype during leaf consumption (assume tissue toxin content equals ingested toxin):\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item Homozygotes (AA and KK): $V_{max} = 12.0$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol toxin detoxified\\\\,g$^{-1}$ larval dry mass\\\\,hr$^{-1}$\\n  \\\\item Heterozygote (AK): Both enzyme variants functional. For each toxin: $V_{max,AK} = 0.7\\\\,V_{max}$, $K_m$ same as corresponding homozygote.\\n  \\\\item Michaelis constants: $K_{m,A} = 5.0$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol\\\\,g$^{-1}$ (GSL); $K_{m,K} = 2.5$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol\\\\,g$^{-1}$ (BDL).\\n  \\\\item Detoxification rate (for each toxin): $V_{detox} = \\\\dfrac{V_{max}\\\\ [Toxin]}{K_m + [Toxin]}$\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\nPlant net CO$_2$ assimilation (exclusive of respiration; no plant or soil microbial respiration occurs):\\n\\\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\\\item For each plant: $P_{net}$ (\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$\\\\,g$^{-1}$ leaf\\\\,hr$^{-1}$) $= P_{max} \\\\cdot e^{0.7\\\\Psi_{soil}}$\\n  \\\\item $P_{max,Arabidopsis} = 35.0$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$\\\\,g$^{-1}$\\\\,hr$^{-1}$\\n  \\\\item $P_{max,Kalanchoe} = 13.0$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$\\\\,g$^{-1}$\\\\,hr$^{-1}$ (assume measurements during daytime, when CAM fixation rate is 60\\\\% of maximal value)\\n\\\\end{itemize}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Question:} What is the net rate of change of atmospheric CO$_2$ concentration in the microcosm (in parts per million per hour, ppm\\\\,hr$^{-1}$) \\\\emph{immediately after} equilibrium is reached under the above drought conditions? Assume all values (ingestion, detoxification, respiration, photosynthesis) are constant at this time; ignore CO$_2$ exchange with soil or experimental apparatus. Use the atmospheric conversion: $1$\\\\,ppm CO$_2$ $= 24.6$\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol CO$_2$ in $600$\\\\,L at $298.15$\\\\,K and $1$\\\\,atm. Present all necessary calculations, but your \\\\textbf{final answer} should be \\\\textbf{only} the net CO$_2$ change rate in ppm\\\\,hr$^{-1}$.\\n\\n\\\\begin{table}[h!]\\n  \\\\centering\\n  \\\\caption{Summary of Genotype Properties and Feeding Preferences}\\n  \\\\begin{tabular}{lccc}\\n    \\\\toprule\\n    Genotype & Population & Feeding Source(s) & $V_{max}$ per pathway (\\\\,$\\\\mu$mol\\\\,g$^{-1}$\\\\,hr$^{-1}$) \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\midrule\\n    AA & 120 & \\\\textit{Arabidopsis} (100\\\\%) & 12.0 (GSL only) \\\\\\\\\\n    AK & 105 & Both (50\\\\% each) & 8.4 (GSL), 8.4 (BDL) \\\\\\\\\\n    KK & 75 & \\\\textit{Kalanchoe} (100\\\\%) & 12.0 (BDL only) \\\\\\\\\\n    \\\\bottomrule\\n  \\\\end{tabular}\\n\\\\end{table}\

question: An experiment investigates the transcriptional and physiological consequences of elevated H3K27me3 deposition at the \\\\\\\\textit{YUCCA6} locus during thermomemory and gravitropism in the model plant \\\\\\\\textit{Arabidopsis thaliana}.\\n\\n\\\\\\\\textbf{Biological context:} In the wild-type (WT), the histone demethylase JMJ30 is required for resetting repressive methylation (H3K27me3) at heat-inducible gene loci. question: A closed population of insular deer (\\\\textit{Cervus insulae}) has been experimentally engineered to express a homozygous gain-of-function allele \\\\textit{mem}\\\\textsuperscript{+} in the GluN2B subunit of the hippocampal CA1 pyramidal neuron NMDA receptor. This allele increases the mean time each receptor channel spends open upon synaptic activation, enhancing memory capacity but increasing neuronal calcium (Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+}) influx and, correspondingly, hippocampal energy cost. \\n\\nA. \\\\textbf{Neurobiological Details:}\\n\\nAll CA1 neurons are isopotential, each with a soma membrane area of $A_\\\\mathrm{mem} = 2100\\\\ \\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2$ evenly divided among $N_\\\\mathrm{syn} = 30{,}000$ glutamatergic synapses per neuron. Each synapse contains $N_\\\\mathrm{NMDAR} = 5$ GluN2B NMDA receptor channels, all with an individual channel permeability $P_\\\\mathrm{Ca} = 6.0\\\\times10^{-17}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{m}^3\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{V}^{-1}$, and each channel occupies $a_\\\\mathrm{ch} = 20\\\\ \\\\mathrm{nm}^2$ of membrane. \\n\\nFor each synaptic event, an NMDAR channel opens with probability $p_\\\\mathrm{open} = 0.35$, and the mean open time is $\\\\tau_\\\\mathrm{open,mem^{+}} = 150.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{ms}$. Synaptic drive is a stationary Poisson process with mean activation frequency $\\\\nu_\\\\mathrm{syn} = 4.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{Hz}$ per synapse. \\n\\nDuring channel open state, the membrane potential is voltage clamped at $V_\\\\mathrm{m,open} = -20.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mV}$; in all other periods, channels are closed and negligible calcium influx occurs. The extracellular and intracellular Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+} concentrations are $[\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{out} = 2.0\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{m}^{-3}$ and $[\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{in} = 5.0\\\\times10^{-5}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{m}^{-3}$ respectively. \\n\\nThe Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz equation for a single channel's Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+} current is:\\n\\\\begin{equation*}\\nI_{\\\\mathrm{Ca}} = z^2 F^2 \\\\frac{A_\\\\mathrm{ch} P_\\\\mathrm{Ca} V_\\\\mathrm{m}}{R T} \\\\frac{[\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{in} - [\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{out} \\\\exp\\\\left(-\\\\frac{z F V_\\\\mathrm{m}}{R T}\\\\right)}{1-\\\\exp\\\\left(-\\\\frac{z F V_\\\\mathrm{m}}{R T}\\\\right)}\\n\\\\end{equation*}\\nwhere $z = 2$, $F = 96\\\\,485\\\\ \\\\mathrm{C}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$, $R = 8.314\\\\ \\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{K}^{-1}$, temperature $T = 310\\\\ \\\\mathrm{K}$, and $M_\\\\mathrm{Ca} = 40.078\\\\ \\\\mathrm{g}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$. Assume all ions entering through these channels are retained in the cytosol (buffering/extrusion compensation is ignored; see note). \\n\\nB. \\\\textbf{Population Details:}\\n\\nThe deer population is at carrying capacity $N_\\\\mathrm{deer} = 50\\\\,000$, each with $N_\\\\mathrm{CA1} = 5.0\\\\times 10^6$ CA1 pyramidal neurons. \\n\\nC. \\\\textbf{Experimental Context:} No other sources of calcium influx are present except the NMDAR channels described. All neurons remain healthy for exactly one sidereal year ($t_\\\\mathrm{year} = 3.156\\\\times10^{7}\\\\ \\\\mathrm{s}$). Note: You may assume that overlap of synaptic events or channel-open events is negligible, so total Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+} charge influx sums linearly over channels, neurons, and deer for the time interval.  \\n\\n\\\\textbf{Table 1. Relevant Constants and Parameters}\\n\\\\begin{table}[h]\\n\\\\begin{tabular}{l l l}\\nParameter & Value & Units \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\n$A_\\\\mathrm{mem}$ & $2100$ & $\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{m}^2$ per neuron \\\\\\\\\\n$N_\\\\mathrm{syn}$ & $3.0\\\\times10^4$ & synapses per neuron \\\\\\\\\\n$N_\\\\mathrm{NMDAR}$ & $5$ & channels per synapse \\\\\\\\\\n$a_\\\\mathrm{ch}$ & $20$ & $\\\\mathrm{nm}^2$ per channel \\\\\\\\\\n$P_\\\\mathrm{Ca}$ & $6.0\\\\times10^{-17}$ & $\\\\mathrm{m}^3\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{V}^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$V_\\\\mathrm{m,open}$ & $-20.0$ & mV \\\\\\\\\\n$T$ & $310$ & K \\\\\\\\\\n$F$ & $96\\\\,485$ & $\\\\mathrm{C}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$R$ & $8.314$ & $\\\\mathrm{J}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{K}^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$z$ & $2$ & unitless \\\\\\\\\\n$[\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{out}$ & $2.0$ & $\\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{m}^{-3}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$[\\\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}]_\\\\mathrm{in}$ & $5\\\\times10^{-5}$ & $\\\\mathrm{mol}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{m}^{-3}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$N_\\\\mathrm{CA1}$ & $5.0\\\\times10^6$ & neurons per deer \\\\\\\\\\n$N_\\\\mathrm{deer}$ & $5.0\\\\times10^4$ & deer \\\\\\\\\\n$t_\\\\mathrm{year}$ & $3.156\\\\times10^7$ & s \\\\\\\\\\n$M_\\\\mathrm{Ca}$ & $40.078$ & $\\\\mathrm{g}\\\\cdot\\\\mathrm{mol}^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$p_\\\\mathrm{open}$ & $0.35$ & unitless \\\\\\\\\\n$\\\\tau_\\\\mathrm{open,mem^{+}}$ & $0.150$ & s \\\\\\\\\\n$\\\\nu_\\\\mathrm{syn}$ & $4.0$ & Hz \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\end{tabular}\\n\\\\end{table}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Question:}\\n\\n\\\\emph{Calculate the total mass (in milligrams, mg) of Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+} ions that enter the entire population of CA1 pyramidal neurons (across all deer on the island) through NMDAR channels over exactly one sidereal year. Express your answer with three significant digits.}\\n\\n\\\\textbf{Note:} Assume Ca\\\\textsuperscript{2+} influx is strictly limited to the open time of NMDAR channels as described. Ignore calcium buffering, extrusion, and any other sources or sinks.\

question: A neurophysiologist is studying energy-dependent synaptic vesicle release at the calyx of Held in a wild-type C57BL/6J mouse at 37\u00b0C under moderate, physiologically relevant hypoxia (7% O\u2082, 93% N\u2082; arterial pO\u2082 ~50 mmHg), perfused with oxygenated artificial cerebrospinal fluid (aCSF). The nerve terminal has a spherical geometry with volume $V_{term} = 4.00~\\\\mathrm{pL}$. \\\\newline\\n\\n#### Experimental Protocol:\\nA 250 Hz stimulus train is delivered to the afferent fiber for 120 ms. Each action potential causes synchronous fusion of vesicles from the readily releasable pool (RRP). Vesicle pool replenishment from the reserve pool is negligible during this interval.\\\\newline\\n\\n#### System Data and Parameters:\\n- **Readily Releasable Pool (RRP):**\\n    - Maximum RRP size: $N_{\\\\mathrm{RRP,max}} = 1500$ vesicles\\n    - Steady-state RRP size is reduced under hypoxia according to:\\n      $$N_{\\\\mathrm{RRP}} = N_{\\\\mathrm{RRP,max}} \\\\times \\\\left[1 - 0.20 \\\\left(1 - \\\\frac{[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{ss}}{[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{norm}}\\\\right) \\\\right]$$\\n    - Each vesicle in the RRP has a fixed probability of release ($p_r$) for each action potential: $p_r = 0.36$\\n- **ATP Dynamics:**\\n    - At steady state (before stimulation), terminal ATP concentration: $[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{ss}$\\n    - Normoxic ATP concentration: $[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{norm} = 2.8~\\\\mathrm{mM}$\\n    - Hypoxic ATP concentration: $[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{ss} = [\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{norm} - \\\\Delta[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]$\\n    - $\\\\Delta[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]$ is determined by the balance of ATP synthesis vs. hydrolysis (see below).\\n- **ATP Synthesis & Consumption:**\\n    - Mitochondria: $N_{\\\\mathrm{mito}} = 1300$ mitochondria/terminal\\n    - Terminal mitochondrial volume fraction: $f_{mito} = 0.13$\\n    - \\n      Glycolytic ATP synthesis: $J_{gly} = 2.1 \\\\times 10^{-18}~\\\\mathrm{mol} \\\\cdot \\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$ (constant)\\n    - \\n      Oxidative ATP synthesis: $J_{mito} = f_{O_2,cap} \\\\cdot J_{mito,max}$\\n    - \\n        $f_{O_2,cap} = 0.83$ (fractional cap due to hypoxia)\\n    - \\n        $J_{mito,max}$ is computed as:\\n        $$J_{mito,max} = N_{\\\\mathrm{mito}} \\\\cdot V_{mito,avg} \\\\cdot k_{cat,CII} \\\\cdot [\\\\mathrm{succinate}]_{mito} \\\\cdot \\\\left(\\\\frac{[\\\\mathrm{O}_2]}{K_{m,O_2} + [\\\\mathrm{O}_2]}\\\\right) \\\\cdot \\\\mathrm{P/O}_{succ}$$\\n        Where:\\n        \\n        - $V_{mito,avg} = 0.40~\\\\mathrm{pL}/N_{\\\\mathrm{mito}}$\\n        - $k_{cat,CII} = 80.0~\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$\\n        - $[\\\\mathrm{succinate}]_{mito} = 0.98~\\\\mathrm{mM}$\\n        - $[\\\\mathrm{O}_2] = 80~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$ (hypoxic aCSF, saturated)\\n        - $K_{m,O_2} = 10~\\\\mu\\\\mathrm{M}$\\n        - $\\\\mathrm{P/O}_{succ} = 1.5$ mol ATP per mol succinate oxidized\\n    - \\n      Total ATP hydrolysis: $J_{hyd} = k_{hyd} \\\\cdot [\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{ss} \\\\cdot V_{term}$, with $k_{hyd} = 1.30~\\\\mathrm{s}^{-1}$\\n- **Stimulation Parameters:**\\n    - Number of action potentials: $N_{AP} = (250~\\\\mathrm{Hz}) \\\\times (0.120~\\\\mathrm{s}) = 30$\\n    - Vesicle pool replenishment is negligible on this timescale.\\n- **Assumptions:**\\n    - Terminal is in steady-state for ATP before the stimulus.\\n    - All parameters are at 37\u00b0C unless otherwise stated.\\n    - RRP depletion follows simple binomial statistics for $N_{AP}$ trials with probability $p_r$, no replacement.\\n\\n#### Table 1: Key Constants\\n\\n\\\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\\n\\\\hline\\nParameter & Value & Units \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\n$N_{\\\\mathrm{mito}}$ & $1300$ & mitochondria/terminal \\\\\\\\\\n$V_{mito,avg}$ & $0.40/1300$ & pL/mitochondrion \\\\\\\\\\n$V_{term}$ & $4.00$ & pL \\\\\\\\\\n$k_{cat,CII}$ & $80.0$ & s$^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$[\\\\mathrm{succinate}]_{mito}$ & $0.98$ & mM \\\\\\\\\\n$\\\\mathrm{P/O}_{succ}$ & $1.5$ & mol ATP/mol succinate \\\\\\\\\\n$[\\\\mathrm{O}_2]$ & $80$ & $\\\\mu$M \\\\\\\\\\n$K_{m,O_2}$ & $10$ & $\\\\mu$M \\\\\\\\\\n$J_{gly}$ & $2.1 \\\\times 10^{-18}$ & mol/s \\\\\\\\\\n$k_{hyd}$ & $1.30$ & s$^{-1}$ \\\\\\\\\\n$[\\\\mathrm{ATP}]_{norm}$ & $2.8$ & mM \\\\\\\\\\n\\\\hline\\n\\\\end{tabular}\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Question:**\\n\\nCalculate the *total number of vesicles released from the terminal during the 250 Hz, 120 ms stimulus train*, given these data and assuming all necessary physiological conversions. Round your answer to the nearest integer.\
claude_sonnet_4_answer:
Looking at this problem, I need to find the steady-state ATP concentration first, then calculate the RRP size, and finally determine total vesicle release.

**Step 1: Calculate steady-state ATP concentration**

First, I'll calculate the maximum mitochondrial ATP synthesis rate:
- $V_{mito,avg} = 0.40/1300 = 3.077 \times 10^{-4}$ pL per mitochondrion
- $J_{mito,max} = 1300 \times (3.077 \times 10^{-4} \times 10^{-12}) \times 80.0 \times (0.98 \times 10^{-3}) \times \frac{80 \times 10^{-6}}{10 \times 10^{-6} + 80 \times 10^{-6}} \times 1.5 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23}$
- $J_{mito,max} = 1.089 \times 10^{-17}$ mol/s

Actual mitochondrial synthesis under hypoxia:
- $J_{mito} = 0.83 \times 1.089 \times 10^{-17} = 9.04 \times 10^{-18}$ mol/s

Total ATP synthesis:
- $J_{syn} = J_{gly} + J_{mito} = 2.1 \times 10^{-18} + 9.04 \times 10^{-18} = 1.114 \times 10^{-17}$ mol/s

At steady state, synthesis equals hydrolysis:
- $J_{syn} = k_{hyd} \times [ATP]_{ss} \times V_{term}$
- $1.114 \times 10^{-17} = 1.30 \times [ATP]_{ss} \times (4.00 \times 10^{-12})$
- $[ATP]_{ss} = 2.14$ mM

**Step 2: Calculate RRP size**
- $N_{RRP} = 1500 \times [1 - 0.20(1 - 2.14/2.8)]$
